SIMPLE: ephemeral
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ephemeral
<hw>E*phem"er*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Beginning and ending in a day; existing only, or no longer than, a
day; diurnal; <as>as, an <ex>ephemeral</ex> flower</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Short-lived; existing or continuing for a short time
only.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Ephemeral</xex> popularity.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>V.
Knox.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sentences not of <qex>ephemeral</qex>, but of eternal,
efficacy.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Stephen.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ephemeral fly</b></col> <fld>(Zo⟦oum⟧l.)</fld>, <cd>one
of a group of neuropterous insects, belonging to the genus
<gen>Ephemera</gen> and many allied genera, which live in the adult or
winged state only for a short time. The larv⟦ae⟧ are aquatic; -- called
also <altname>day fly</altname> and <altname>May
fly</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ephemeral</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ephemeral
<hw>E*phem"er*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Anything lasting but a day, or
a brief time; an ephemeral plant, insect, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ephemeran</ent>⟦br⟧
